          1. What is a digital Tuning Fork?
        </h4>
        <p>
          A digital tuning fork generates high-precision, mathematically correct audio sine wave tones. Unlike physical tuning forks that can warp, digital oscillators emit standard reference frequencies perfectly.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">2. Key Features of this Tool</h4>
        <p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-4 flex flex-col gap-1.5 mt-1">
            <li>
              <strong>Pops/Clicks Prevention</strong>: Tones use a short audio attack/release ramp to ensure click-free starts and stops.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>A4 Reference Calibration</strong>: Adjust A4 from 415Hz (Baroque standard) to 466Hz to adapt to historical tuning needs.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Two-Tone Comparison</strong>: Generate beats by adding a secondary tone. Play them together to calibrate intervals or A/B test alternating pitches.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Fine-Adjustment Mode</strong>: Drag the pitch slider in a narrow ±5Hz range to achieve precise sub-Hz frequency control.
